Therefore, I will go with 300 km/s. **Final Answer** The component of the star's velocity parallel to the Earth's vector is \boxed{300} kilometers per second. </think> To determine the component of the star's velocity parallel to the Earth's vector (radial velocity), we use the Doppler shift formula: \[ \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\lambda} = \frac{v_r}{c} \] Given: - Rest wavelength (\(\lambda\)) = 5007 Å - Observed wavelength (\(\lambda + \Delta \lambda\)) = 5012 Å - Speed of light (\(c\)) = \(3 \times 10^8\) m/s First, calculate the change in wavelength (\(\Delta \lambda\)): \[ \Delta \lambda = 5012 \, \text{Å} - 5007 \, \text{Å} = 5 \, \text{Å} \] Next, compute the fractional change in wavelength: \[ \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\lambda} = \frac{5}{5007} \approx 0.0009986 \] Using the Doppler shift formula to find the radial velocity (\(v_r\)): \[ v_r = \left( \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\lambda} \right) \times c \approx 0.0009986 \times 3 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s} \approx 299,580 \, \text{m/s} \approx 299.6 \, \text{km/s} \] Considering the significant figures, the distance to the star is given as 60 parsecs (two significant figures). Therefore, the radial velocity should be rounded to two significant figures: \[ v_r \approx 300 \, \text{km/s} \] Thus, the component of the star's velocity parallel to the Earth's vector is \(\boxed{300}\) kilometers per second.
